  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="eyebrow">The Arguments</div>
    <h1>Bitcoin <span class="amber">Spend and Replace</span></h1>
    <p class="subtitle"><em>The most common assumption about taxes when spending bitcoin in the US is wrong. Here&rsquo;s what &ldquo;replace and spend&rdquo; actually buys you, and how to do it cleanly.</em></p>
  </header>

  <!-- ─── BODY ─── -->
  <article class="essay">

    <section class="section">
      <h2>The comforting myth</h2>
      <p class="prose">A persistent piece of Bitcoiner folklore holds that if you spend bitcoin and immediately buy back the same amount with fresh dollars, the spending event &ldquo;doesn&rsquo;t count&rdquo; for tax purposes &mdash; your bitcoin balance is unchanged, so there&rsquo;s nothing for the IRS to tax. This is wrong. It&rsquo;s a comfortable wrong, and it stays wrong even if everyone you know believes it.</p>
      <p class="prose">It also obscures something more useful. The right version of this practice &mdash; <em>Replace and Spend</em>, in that order, executed with a small amount of discipline &mdash; can reduce the tax on a given transaction to something close to zero. It can&rsquo;t eliminate the taxable event itself (only one move can, and we&rsquo;ll get to it near the end). But &ldquo;close to zero on this spend, with my legacy stack undisturbed&rdquo; is a meaningfully different proposition from &ldquo;no tax at all on anything.&rdquo; It&rsquo;s also the proposition that&rsquo;s actually available.</p>
      <p class="prose">This page is for US Bitcoiners who want to spend bitcoin in the circular economy without surrendering more to the tax man than they have to. It&rsquo;s written to current US federal law as of mid-2026, which is always a moving target &mdash; sometimes in helpful directions. The closing section covers what&rsquo;s pending and what might simplify all of this.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>The reality in one paragraph</h2>
      <p class="prose">Under IRS Notice 2014-21, the foundational guidance from a decade ago, bitcoin is property for federal tax purposes &mdash; not currency.<sup class="fn-mark"><a href="#fn-1" id="fnref-1">1</a></sup> Every time you spend bitcoin on something, you&rsquo;re disposing of property, and you owe capital gains tax on the difference between what those specific units of bitcoin originally cost you (your <em>cost basis</em>) and what they&rsquo;re worth at the moment you spend them. Buying more bitcoin afterward does not retroactively cancel the disposition. The IRS does not recognize what tax professionals call &ldquo;balance-sheet offsets&rdquo; between non-simultaneous transactions. The spend is a completed sale; the repurchase is a new acquisition with new basis. They are two separate events that happen to involve the same asset.</p>
      <p class="prose">This is the <em>net-zero balance illusion</em>. It is the central misconception this page exists to put to bed.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Sequence is everything</h2>
      <p class="prose">The sequence of the two transactions decides which lot of bitcoin gets sold &mdash; and therefore what the gain is.</p>
      <p class="prose"><strong>Spend then Replace.</strong> You spend bitcoin first, then go buy more, immediately after. Under the default IRS accounting method &mdash; First-In, First-Out, or FIFO &mdash; the bitcoin that gets sold is the oldest bitcoin in your account. For most long-term holders, the oldest bitcoin is also the cheapest, bought years ago at a fraction of today&rsquo;s price. Spending those low-basis units triggers the largest possible gain. The replacement purchase just gives you new bitcoin sitting at today&rsquo;s price, which has no effect on the tax you already owe on the spend.</p>
      <p class="prose"><strong>Replace then Spend.</strong> You buy the bitcoin first, then spend it. The newly-acquired bitcoin has a cost basis equal to roughly today&rsquo;s price. If you can identify <em>those specific units</em> as the ones being spent, the gain on the spending transaction is approximately zero &mdash; basis &asymp; sale price, by construction. Your low-basis legacy holdings stay where they are, untouched.</p>
      <p class="prose">The difference between these two sequences, on say a $200 electronics-store spend by someone holding bitcoin at a 10&times; embedded gain, is roughly $30 of capital gains tax versus roughly nothing. Across a year of routine spending, the difference compounds into real money.</p>

